1 Where Do People Drink The Most Beer, Wine And Spirits?

library(fivethirtyeight)
data(drinks)

We have one column with character data which contains country names and four columns with numerical data which contains the amount of each type of alcohol consumed in these countries. There are no missing variables.

desc_beer<- drinks %>% 
  arrange(desc(beer_servings))

top25_beer<-head(desc_beer,25)

ggplot(top25_beer,aes(x=reorder(country,beer_servings),y=beer_servings)) + geom_col(fill="brown") + labs(x="Country", y="Beer Servings", title="Top 25 Beer Consuming Countries") + coord_flip() + theme_clean() + 
  NULL

desc_wine<- drinks %>% 
  arrange(desc(wine_servings))

top25_wine<-head(desc_wine,25)

ggplot(top25_wine,aes(x=reorder(country,wine_servings),y=wine_servings)) + geom_col(fill="maroon") + labs(x="Country", y="Wine Servings", title="Top 25 Wine Consuming Countries") + coord_flip() + theme_clean() + NULL

desc_spirit<- drinks %>% 
  arrange(desc(spirit_servings))

top25_spirit<-head(desc_spirit,25)

ggplot(top25_spirit,aes(x=reorder(country,spirit_servings),y=spirit_servings)) + geom_col(fill="grey") + labs(x="Country", y="Spirit Servings", title="Top 25 Spirit Consuming Countries") + coord_flip() + theme_clean() + NULL

In the first plot we can see that Namibia has the highest yearly consumption of beer per capita. Beer is one of Namibias most iconic commodity and their top quality brewing is a legacy of German colonialism.The second most beer-loving country is Czech Republic, known for its unique brewing methods and prevalent drinking culture. The second plot, representing wine consumption, shows that French and Portuguese drink the most wine. It is not very surprising given these are one of the most well known wine producing countries in the world. Last but not least, looking at the third plot we can see that Grenada and Belarus are the most spirit-loving countries. We can safely assume that Grenadians prefer to drink rum while Belarussians enjoy their vodka.

## Use ggplot to answer the following

  • Examine the relationship between gross and cast_facebook_likes. Produce a scatterplot and write one sentence discussing whether the number of facebook likes that the cast has received is likely to be a good predictor of how much money a movie will make at the box office. What variable are you going to map to the Y- and X- axes?

## Comment gross_fblikes

We chose the Gross as the Y-variable and the Facebook Likes as the X-variable because we believed Gross to be the dependent variable and Facebook Likes the independent one. On average, the number of facebook likes seems to be a good predictor of how well a movie will fare in the box office, however, there are many data points which lie outside this observation and which prove that this isnt always the case.

  • Examine the relationship between gross and budget. Produce a scatterplot and write one sentence discussing whether budget is likely to be a good predictor of how much money a movie will make at the box office.
ggplot(data = movies_clean, mapping = aes(x = budget, y = gross)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method=lm) +  scale_x_log10()  + scale_y_log10() + NULL

## Comment gross_budget

The tendency seems to indicate that the bigger the budget, the higher the movie will gross. This is especially true for movies with high budgets as we see a concentration of datapoints at that level. Some dataponts indicate that it is not always the case as many movies fall outside this high budget - high gross correlation. However, the overarching sense is that budget is likely to be a good predictor of how much money a movie will make at the box office.

  • Examine the relationship between gross and rating. Produce a scatterplot, faceted by genre and discuss whether IMDB ratings are likely to be a good predictor of how much money a movie will make at the box office. Is there anything strange in this dataset?
ggplot(data = movies_clean, mapping = aes(x = rating, y = gross)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method=lm) +  scale_x_log10()  + scale_y_log10() + NULL

## Comment Gross_IMDB

According to the datapoints, IMDB ratings tend to be higher for movies which have grossed highly indicating that IMDB ratings could be a good predictor of how much a movie will make. In reality however, its much more complicated to determine if IMDB scores are high because a movie has grossed highly, in which case it isnt so much a correlation as a causality.

#Calculating daily returns
myStocks_daily_returns <- myStocks %>%
  tq_transmute(select     = adjusted, 
               mutate_fun = periodReturn, 
               period     = "daily", 
               type       = "log",
               col_rename = "daily_returns",
               cols = c(nested.col))

#Calculating monthly  returns
myStocks_monthly_returns <- myStocks %>%
  tq_transmute(select     = adjusted, 
               mutate_fun = periodReturn, 
               period     = "monthly", 
               type       = "arithmetic",
               col_rename = "monthly_returns",
               cols = c(nested.col)) 

#Calculating yearly returns
myStocks_annual_returns <- myStocks %>%
  group_by(symbol) %>%
  tq_transmute(select     = adjusted, 
               mutate_fun = periodReturn, 
               period     = "yearly", 
               type       = "arithmetic",
               col_rename = "yearly_returns",
               cols = c(nested.col))

3.5 Comment on riskiness of selected securities

We can infer that Tesla (TSLA) is the most risky stock given it has the highest standard deviation, displayed by its monthly returns having the fattest tails and shortest peak at the mean value. By contrast, SPY (S&P500 ETF) appears the least risky stock given it displays the lowest standard deviation when comparing monthly returns.

3.6 Plotting risk and reward for a stock

library(ggrepel)
risk_return <- ggplot(data = monthly_returns, mapping = aes(y=mean_return, x=sd_return, label = symbol)) + geom_point(color = "blue")

p <- risk_return + geom_text_repel(aes(label=symbol)) + labs(title = "Risk-Reward Tradeoff for Stocks", x="Standard Deviation of Return", y="Expected Monthly Return") + geom_smooth(method=lm) + theme_calc()
p

## Comment on above graph

From the graph we can see that ANF is the furthest below the trend line, indicating that its returns are much less than expected given the risk a shareholders bears when holding this stock. On the other hand, DPZ seems to strongly outperform given its riskiness.

I am going to clean the data set, as variable names are in capital letters, some variables are not really necessary, and some variables, e.g., education are given as a number rather than a more useful description

hr_cleaned <- hr_dataset %>% 
  clean_names() %>% 
  mutate(
    education = case_when(
      education == 1 ~ "Below College",
      education == 2 ~ "College",
      education == 3 ~ "Bachelor",
      education == 4 ~ "Master",
      education == 5 ~ "Doctor"
    ),
    environment_satisfaction = case_when(
      environment_satisfaction == 1 ~ "Low",
      environment_satisfaction == 2 ~ "Medium",
      environment_satisfaction == 3 ~ "High",
      environment_satisfaction == 4 ~ "Very High"
    ),
    job_satisfaction = case_when(
      job_satisfaction == 1 ~ "Low",
      job_satisfaction == 2 ~ "Medium",
      job_satisfaction == 3 ~ "High",
      job_satisfaction == 4 ~ "Very High"
    ),
    performance_rating = case_when(
      performance_rating == 1 ~ "Low",
      performance_rating == 2 ~ "Good",
      performance_rating == 3 ~ "Excellent",
      performance_rating == 4 ~ "Outstanding"
    ),
    work_life_balance = case_when(
      work_life_balance == 1 ~ "Bad",
      work_life_balance == 2 ~ "Good",
      work_life_balance == 3 ~ "Better",
      work_life_balance == 4 ~ "Best"
    )
  ) %>% 
  select(age, attrition, daily_rate, department,
         distance_from_home, education,
         gender, job_role,environment_satisfaction,
         job_satisfaction, marital_status,
         monthly_income, num_companies_worked, percent_salary_hike,
         performance_rating, total_working_years,
         work_life_balance, years_at_company,
         years_since_last_promotion)

The first graph shows that a correlation between education and income exists - higher education leads to a higher salary. However, there are probably other important factors like job role that influence the monthly income as well.

Looking at the gender/ monthly income graph there is an indication that women earn more money on average, however, the difference does not seem to be significant. In contrast, the male chart shows more outlays at the top. This might reflect a top management dominated by male employees.

Looking at the graph the companys payments seem to be very unequally distributed between the different job roles. For example, managers and research directors are paid on average three times as much as any other job title.

cali_cities <- zip_codes %>%
  filter(state == "CA") %>%
  transform(zip = as.double(zip)) %>%
  select(zip, primary_city)

#Find the donations per city for all candidates
donations_by_city <- donations_by_zip %>%
  inner_join(cali_cities, by = "zip") %>%
  group_by(cand_nm, primary_city) %>%
  summarize(total_by_city = sum(total_by_zip))

#Narrow it down to just the two presidential nominees and their top 10 cities
presidentials <- donations_by_city %>%
  filter(cand_nm == "Trump, Donald J." | cand_nm == "Clinton, Hillary Rodham") %>%
  group_by(cand_nm) %>%
  slice_max(n=10, order_by = total_by_city) %>%
  ungroup()  # mutate(cand_nm = as.factor(cand_nm), reorder_within(primary_city, total_by_city, cand_nm))
